hared memory/quota coordination, testable fully in-process.","test_description":"Instantiate concurrent callers (and, if relevant, multiple client wrappers) sharing account config; fire N async `call()` operations against a stub transport and assert aggregate attempt budget is enforced by one shared quota bucket, not independent per-caller buckets.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.13,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When multiple requests are waiting to be sent, they are dispatched in the order they were originally submitted.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: FIFO correctness depends on interaction between queue data structure, scheduler, and async dispatch path; isolated unit of queue alone can miss reorder during dispatch integration. REAL-INFRA: fake timers + stub sender suffice; no real network/subprocess required. MOCK-HIDE: simplistic mocks that complete immediately may hide reordering under wait conditions. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: not applicable. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) no mandatory OS/network/subprocess, (b) no AI dependency, (c) no multi-agentic chain, (d) no LLM-stage handoff. ADVERSARIAL-CRITIQUE: could be Unit if only a pure queue is under test; behavior text includes 'waiting to be sent' (scheduler+sender path), which is cross-module. REJECTION-GATE: rejected System because FIFO dispatch ordering can be deterministically validated in-process without real HTTP/OS effects.","test_description":"Enqueue multiple `call()` requests rapidly while quota/timing forces waiting, use controlled clock and stub sender, then assert send-invocation order matches submission order and completions do not violate FIFO dispatch.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.06,"Integration":0.78,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.03}}]}
